The most horrible experience we had in a Cantonese seafood restaurant.  The manager is rude.  The waiters are not familiar with their menu.  The kitchen cannot handle the volume.  Skip this one if you are looking for a place to book your banquets or even for a simple family dinner.  We made a reservation for 11 people at 5pm, a week in advance to celebrate the lunar new year.  We arrived 30 minutes early.  There were no other customers here yet.  All the tables were empty.  However, the manager who was still busy setting up, would not let us sit down.  When it was at 5pm, he finally put us in the last table in front of the door.  All the tables were still empty.  When we asked to be placed away from the draft, he pushed the table a little bit away from the door but said he needed our table back by 7:30pm!  When we ordered our dishes directly from their menu, the waiter didn’t know they were listed.  For example, he didn’t know they offer “Lemongrass with shrimp”.  He said he would write it down and see what would happen.  We ordered dungeon crab, scallops, shrimp, lamb, chicken, pork chops, noodles and rice.  All the typical Cantonese dishes.  The dishes came out one by one except one.  At around 6:30pm, we reminded them of the missing dish of “golden and silver egg fried rice”.  One waiter said they knew and the kitchen was very busy.  At around 7pm, another waiter said the rice was not cooked right and asked whether we wanted to cancel that dish.  However, 5 minutes later, he came out with a rice dish (Yeung Chow).  We just wanted to make sure this was not meant for a different table.  He said he would change the bill for the price difference.  It seemed that the chef didn’t know how to cook what we ordered.  By this time, we were too exhausted.  We just ate the last dish and paid our bill of $300 in cash, before 7:30pm.  After the owner took the money, while we were still sitting, the waiter came pouring tea and water on the Lazy Susan and said they needed the table back.  I looked around. There were at least two big round empty tables.  I can understand it is not easy to run a restaurant and they are still learning.  They, however, do not seem to care about the customer experience.  Not a single word to apologize for all the mix ups.  They made us feel like they were doing us a favor.  What an outrageous place!  They should not work in the service industry.

Place just opened this week. I came here for Chinese New Year with at least 60 people in my dinner party. For such a large group, they haven't figured out the pace in the kitchen yet. Some tables received food at different intervals about 15 mins apart initially.  Food- Food is typical, slightly greasy Chinese food  Service- Waiters were very attentive. They checked on us frequently. However, they're definitely new to the industry- you can tell because some of them don't know how to use the double spoon serving trick.  Cleanliness- Place is new so it's clean, so refreshing since most Chinese restaurants are dirty.  Advice- give it at least a month before coming to this place, even if this was a smaller party, the restaurant was packed and they were stretched thin and had a hard time keeping pace.  Pictures- delicious lamb chops (4/5, tender and juicy but a little too salty), shark fin soup (no rating, did not consume), oysters and broccoli and bok choy (3/5, used dried oysters and scallops and tasted rubbery), roast chicken (5/5, perfectly crispy skin and moist)
